'''Mumia Abu-Jamal''' (born '''Wesley Cook''' [[April 24]], [[1954]]<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =Pennsylvania Department of Corrections
  | title =Persons sentenced to execution in Pennsylvania as of August 1, 2007
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.cor.state.pa.us/portal/lib/portal/Execution_List
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>) is a former [[Black Panther Party]] [[activist]], cab driver and journalist from [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] [[conviction|convicted]] for the [[murder]] of [[police officer]] [[Daniel Faulkner]] in 1981. He is serving a presently undefined [[Sentence (law)|sentence]] of [[imprisonment]] at State Correctional Institution - Greene near [[Waynesburg, Pennsylvania]] in consequence. Originally [[Capital punishment|sentenced to death]], that sentence was quashed and resentencing ordered in December 2001 by a [[judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania]]. Both he and the [[Commonwealth of Pennsylvania]] have [[appeal (law)|appealed]] the [[court ruling|ruling]] alternately as to the appropriateness of affirming the conviction and that of disaffirming the validity of the original sentence. 

His [[cause celebre|celebrated case]] has received [[international]] attention. Supporters and human rights campaigners variously assert that he is innocent, that the incident in question was a [[Actual innocence|setup]], that he did not receive a [[fair trial]], and/or express their opposition to the possibility of the administration of the [[death penalty]]. Skeptics and opponents assert that he is [[guilt (law)|guilty]], that he received the benefit of [[due process]] and was legitimately [[conviction|convicted]] of murder. Execution proponents among these assert that under Pennsylvania law, his eventual [[judicial execution]] is warranted and mandated by the nature of his crime.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Amnesty International: new trial
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://web.amnesty.org/library/Index/engAMR510012000 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =Court TV
  | title =Guilty and Framed 
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.courttv.com/archive/casefiles/mumia/guilty.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =European Parliament
  | title =European Parliament resolution (p. 39 of original, 49 of pdf
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.europarl.europa.eu/calendar/calendar?APP=PDF&TYPE=PV2&FILE=19950921EN.pdf&LANGUE=EN  
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

The attention received has spawned [[controversy|controversies]] surrounding [[toponymy|naming of public places]]; his status as an [[Honorary degree|honoree]] of [[municipal]], educational and [[civil society]] organizations; and his engagement as a [[radio host]], [[writer]] and [[commencement speaker]]. During the period of his imprisonment he has continued his activism as a spoken word commentator and as a published author of several works - most notably ''[[Live from Death Row]]''.

== Early life, activism, journalism career ==
[[Image:WPhilaDistrict.PNG|thumb|right|200px|Philadelphia region map demonstrating the location of [[West Philadelphia]], which is inclusive of Powelton]][[Image:Bpp logo.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Black Panther Party logo]]Born Wesley Cook, he was given the name Mumia in 1968 by his [[high school]] [[teacher]], a [[Kenyan]] instructing a class on [[African culture]]s in which [[student]]s took African [[classroom]] [[names]].<ref name= "Buroughs-Ind">{{cite web
  | last =Burroughs
  | first =Todd Steven 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Ready to Party: Mumia Abu-Jamal and the Black Panther Party (Index)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.tcnj.edu/~kpearson/Mumia/index.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =}}</ref> He formally [[adopt]]ed the name appending Abu-Jamal as his choice of [[surname]] after the birth of his son Jamal on July 18, 1971.<ref>ibid.</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =Burroughs
  | first =Todd Steven 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Ready to Party: Mumia Abu-Jamal and the Black Panther Party (Part 4)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.tcnj.edu/~kpearson/Mumia/parrt4.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =}}</ref> "Mumia" is [[Luhya|Luhya language]] in origin. Abu-Jamal means "[[father]] of Jamal" in [[Arabic language|Arabic]]. He has not at any point asserted that his choice of name relates to [[Conversion to Islam#Conversion to Islam|religious conversion to Islam]] and he has never asserted that he is a [[Muslim]]. He expresses his religious beliefs, which follow no denomination, in his [[poetry]] [[book]] "''Death Blossoms''", wherein he continually expresses a belief in a Mother God who coexists with all [[male]] religious understandings and which he chooses to refer to by the name of "Mama".<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =Abu-Jamal, Mumia
  | title =Death Blossoms
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://planetgrenada.blogspot.com/2005/05/mumia-abu-jamal-death-blossoms.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =}}
</ref>

He described the circumstance of "being kicked into the Black Panther Party" through suffering a beating at the hands of [[white people|white]] [[racist]]s and [[police]] at the same time as being charged with [[assault]] for his efforts to disrupt a [[George Wallace#Independent American Party presidential candidate|George Wallace for President]] rally in 1968.<ref name="CCK1092">{{cite web
  | last =Kissinger
  | first =C. Clark 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =On a Move, The Story of Mumia Abu-Jamal (Book review)
Book review
  | work =Revolutionary Worker #1092
  | publisher =
  | date =February 25, 2001
  | url =http://www.rwor.org/a/v22/1090-99/1092/bisson_mumia.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =}}
</ref> In 1969 he helped form Philadelphia’s branch of the [[Black Panther Party]]<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Burroughs
  | first =Todd Steven
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =Abu-Jamal, Mumia
