  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> Mazi’s mother is his second former wife, Marilyn a.k.a. "Peachie".<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Burroughs
  | first =Todd Steven 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Ready to Party: Mumia Abu-Jamal and the Black Panther Party (Part 4)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.tcnj.edu/~kpearson/Mumia/parrt4.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

After leaving the Panthers he returned to high school, was elected the president of the student body, then expelled because of his actions in leading protests to change the school name to [[Malcolm X]] High.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Kissinger
  | first =C. Clark 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =On a Move, The Story of Mumia Abu-Jamal (Book review)
  | work =Revolutionary Worker #1092
  | publisher =
  | date =February 25, 2001
  | url =http://www.rwor.org/a/v22/1090-99/1092/bisson_mumia.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> For a number of semesters thereafter he studied at Goddard College in rural [[Vermont]] and attained some broadcasting industry experience at its student radio station.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Kissinger
  | first =C. Clark 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =On a Move, The Story of Mumia Abu-Jamal (Book review)
  | work =Revolutionary Worker #1092
  | publisher =
  | date =February 25, 2001
