  | accessdate =  }}</ref> 

As a radio [[journalist]] he was renowned for identifying with and giving exposure to the [[MOVE]] militant activist back-to-nature community in Philadelphia's [[Powelton Village]] neighborhood including reportage of the 1979-80 trial of certain of its members (the "MOVE Nine") charged with the murder of police officer James Ramp.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mediafilter.org biographical information on Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://mediafilter.org/MFF/Mumia.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> He predicted that their [[Commune (intentional community)|commune]] would be attacked, and in 1985 the MOVE house was indeed [[Firebombing|firebombed]] by police during a stand-off between MOVE members and city officials - killing 11 people and destroying an entire row of houses.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =20th Anniversary of Move Bombing
  | work =
  | publisher =Metafilter.com community weblog
  | date =May 12, 2005 
  | url =http://www.metafilter.com/41954/20th-Anniversary-of-MOVE-bombing
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>
At the time of the killing of Daniel Faulkner, Abu-Jamal worked as a [[taxicab]] driver for the United Cab Company in Philadelphia.<ref>As stated in "''All Things Censored''" by Mumia Abu-Jamal (also mentioning his early journalism career)</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
