== Murder, arrest, trial ==
{{main|1982 trial of Mumia Abu-Jamal}}
{{seealso|Mumia Abu-Jamal legal proceedings}}

[[Image:Daniel faulkner.jpg|right|thumb|Daniel Faulkner]] 
In the early hours of December 9, 1981, around 3:51 a.m., [[Philadelphia Police Department]] officer [[Daniel Faulkner]] was shot and killed during an altercation that ensued from a routine [[traffic stop]] of a vehicle driven by [[William Cook (street vendor)|William Cook]], Abu-Jamal's younger brother.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial and post-conviction relief hearing transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref> 
The following sequence of events was presented in evidence by the [[prosecution]] before the [[jury]] at his [[Trial (law)|trial]]<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>: 
<blockquote>1. During the traffic stop, Cook [[assault]]ed Faulkner, who in turn attempted to subdue Cook.<br /> 
2. Abu Jamal emerged from a nearby parking lot and shot Faulkner in the [[back]].<br /> 
3. Faulkner was able to return fire, seriously wounding Abu-Jamal.<br />
4. Abu Jamal then advanced on Faulkner, fired some additional shots at close range, one of which struck Faulkner in the face causing his death.<br />  
5. Abu Jamal was unable to flee due to his own [[gunshot injury|gunshot wound]], and was taken into [[arrest|custody]] by other police officers, who had been summoned by Faulkner at the time of the traffic stop.<br /></blockquote> 

In Abu-Jamal's possession was a [[.38 Special|.38 caliber]] [[revolver]] that records showed he had purchased in 1979. The [[Cylinder (firearms)|cylinder]] of the revolver had five spent [[Cartridge (firearms)|cartridges]]. He was taken directly from the scene of the shooting to a hospital and was treated for his injury. [[Witness]]es, including a [[security guard]] working at the hospital, stated that while Abu-Jamal was receiving medical treatment, he acknowledged that he shot Daniel Faulkner (see [[Mumia Abu-Jamal#"Hospital bed" confession|"Hospital bed" confession]]). 

He was [[indictment|charged]] with [[first-degree murder]]. He initially retained the services of [[Defense (legal)|criminal defense]] [[attorney]] Anthony Jackson. In May 1982 he announced that he would [[Pro se|represent himself]], with Jackson continuing to act as his [[legal advice|legal advisor]]. The [[judge]] initially acquiesced to this but, in time, reversed his attitude of acceptance citing the effect of Abu-Jamal's deemed "disruptive" behavior in the court.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Day 1 Transcript of 1982 trial, from 1.82 for the rest of the day
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-17-82.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> 
[[Image:Philadelphia City Hall (from Art Museum).JPG|thumb|right|180px|Philadelphia City Hall, shown in 2006]]
Abu-Jamal repeatedly and vociferously [[dissent]]ed from accepting the judge's [[court ruling|rulings]] on [[question of law|points of law]] to the extent that he was removed from representing himself and it was [[court order|ordered]] that Jackson resume the role of acting as his sole [[advocate]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> In all he was removed from the courtroom at least 13 times during the course of the legal proceedings and trial by reason of what the judge deemed to be intentionally disruptive actions on his part.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (see pp.3,104)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf
  | format =PDF
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>
The [[Legal case|case]] went to trial in June 1982 at [[Philadelphia City Hall|Philadelphia's City Hall]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts, see p.2
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

=== Prosecution witnesses at trial ===
Four eyewitnesses to the shooting were produced by the [[prosecution]]:
 
<blockquote>1. Robert Chobert, a [[taxicab|cab]] [[driving|driver]];<br /> 
2. Michael Scanlon, a [[businessman]] who had been visiting from out of town on the night of the killing;<br /> 
3. Cynthia White, a [[prostitute]] who was later revealed to be a [[police informant]];<br />
4. Albert Magilton, a [[pedestrian]]<br /></blockquote>  

These witnesses testified to the effect that they were at the scene at the time of the shooting, and each identified Abu-Jamal as the person who shot Daniel Faulkner.
<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref>

==== Controversion of prosecution witnesses ====
While Cynthia White testified to witnessing the shootings from a nearby corner, Dessie Hightower has stated that he observed her to be at least half a block further away. 
<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia Jamal: A Case for Reasonable Doubt? (Part 2 of Youtube video, at 10:14)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bAUfPYt3waA
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite video
| people = Mumia Abu-Jamal
| title = Mumia Abu-Jamal: A Case for Reasonable Doubt? 
| medium = DVD of HBO TV Special
| publisher = Otmoor Productions
| location = London, UK
| date = 1997 }}</ref> 

Prostitute Veronica Jones testified at trial that she had been offered favourable treatment by police on condition that she corroborate Cynthia White.<ref>>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia Jamal: A Case for Reasonable Doubt? (Part 3 of Youtube video)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rme-niN_jZY
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

Robert Chobert originally told police that shooter had run away.{{Citation
