==== "''Hospital bed''" confession ====
The prosecution presented three additional witnesses: security officer Priscilla Durham and two members of the [[Philadelphia Police Department]], who testified that while Abu-Jamal was being treated for gunshot wounds he had at least once or even twice proclaimed:<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Bissinger
  | first =Buzz 
  | coauthors =
  | title =The Famous And The Dead
  | work =
  | pages =p.10
  | language =
  | publisher =[[Vanity Fair]]
  | date =August 1999
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/VanityFair.pdf 
  | accessdate =  }}</ref><ref>http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf December 2001 US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn which relates "[Abu-Jamal] was heard to twice say that “I shot the [[motherfucker]], and I hope the motherfucker dies.” In some places, including places in the 1982 trial transcript, the attributed statement is recorded as "I shot the motherfucker and I hope he dies."</ref>{{cquote|I shot the motherfucker, and I hope the motherfucker dies.}}

Other witnesses are recorded as having reported that Abu-Jamal was completely [[unconsciousness|unconscious]] during the time that he was reported to have uttered it.<ref>http://www.freemumia.org/intro.html ''Who is mumia?'' from mumia.org incorporating the statement "Abu-Jamal's doctor said that Abu-Jamal, who was unconscious, said nothing. He reported that a nurse found police with loaded guns pointed at Mumia as he lay unconscious in his hospital bed."</ref> 

The original report of Gary Wakshul, a police officer who confirms to having accompanied him throughout the entire period of his arrest and medical treatment, states that "the negro male made no comments". Officer Wakshul elsewhere later stated that he witnessed Abu-Jamal's utterance of the "hospital bed" confession on the night of the killing, such statement being made almost three months after the arrest and upon the occasion when the prosecutor met with police seeking to test the evidence about Abu-Jamal's alleged utterance of it. Wakshul is recorded as having reasoned that he "didn't think the confession was important" at the time he wrote his original report.{{Citation
  | last =Weinglass
  | first =Leonard
  | author-link =
  | last2 =
  | first2 =
  | author2-link =
  | title =Update to Race for Justice
  | newspaper =Revolutionary Worker 
  | pages =
  | year =#925
  | date =September 28, 1997 
  | url = http://revcom.us/a/v19/920-29/925/wein.htm}}
 Judge [[Albert F. Sabo]] did not permit the trial jury to receive Gary Wakshul's original report as evidence.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref>

=== Defense witnesses at trial ===
==== "''Running man''" defense ====
A number of witnesses made statements - either to police on the scene or in court testimony or both - describing the fact of one or more men running along the street shortly after the shooting.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Komisar
  | first =Lucy
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia Abu-Jamal 101 
  | work =
  | publisher =Albion Monitor
  | date =December 17, 1998
  | url =http://www.albionmonitor.com/9812a/mumiaback.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> At trial, the defense presented statements made by four of these witnesses: Deborah Kordansky, Robert Chobert, Veronica Jones, and Desie Hightower.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>  

This became known as the "running man theory", based on the possibility that a "running man" may have been the actual shooter. Of those witnesses, only Chobert averred to actually witnessing the shooting. He testified that shortly after the shooting he had told police that he had seen Abu-Jamal shoot Daniel Faulkner in the face, and that Abu-Jamal had then run a short distance and collapsed on the sidewalk - himself having also been shot by Faulkner. In other words, Chobert's testimony was that ''Abu-Jamal himself'' was the running man.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>  

The remaining three witnesses made various statements about a man or men running in or away from the area. None of them claimed that the running man, or men, were involved in the shooting.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref>

=== Witnesses not called at trial ===
{{seealso|Mumia Abu-Jamal legal proceedings#New witnesses}}
Several material and potentially material witnesses were not called to testify at trial. Some were subsequently heard from at post-conviction review hearings in the period 1995-7 or otherwise had their statements incorporated into appeal briefs filed on behalf of Abu-Jamal. 

Abu-Jamal did not testify in his own defense. Regarding this he has explained:<blockquote>"At my trial I was denied the [[right]] to [[self-defense|defend myself]]. I had no confidence in my [[public defender|court-appointed attorney]], who never even asked me what happened the night I was shot and the police officer was killed; and I was excluded from at least half the trial. ''Since I was denied all my rights at my trial I did not testify. I would not be used to make it look like I had a fair trial''."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =May 2001
  | url =http://www.chicagofreemumia.org/mumiadecl.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref></blockquote>
Abu-Jamal did not state his version of events for the initial [[police]] [[investigation]], nor for almost another 20 years afterwards until subsequent to his third set of [[lawyer]]s offering the 1999 [[affidavit]] of [[Arnold Beverly]]. Beverly purported to [[Confession (legal)|confess]] that he was in fact the person who had shot Daniel Faulkner as part of a [[contract killing]] connected with a desire to keep Faulkner from interfering with [[political corruption|graft and payoffs]] to [[police corruption|corrupt police]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Affidavit of Arnold Beverly
  | work =
  | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
  | date =June 8, 1999 
  | url =http://www.freemumia.com/beverlydeclaration.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> 

Abu-Jamal's May 2001 [[oath|sworn]] statement [[wikt:aver|avers]] that he had been sitting in his cab across the street when he first heard shouting, then saw a police vehicle, then heard the sound of gunshots. It further asserts that, upon seeing his brother standing in the street staggering and appearing disoriented Abu-Jamal ran across the street to him and was shot by a uniformed police officer. It also incorporates Abu-Jamal's claim to have been [[torture]]d by the police while he was still in need of medical assistance for his wounds. It concludes with his claim of innocence: {{cquote|"I never said I shot the policeman. I did not shoot the policeman. I never said I hoped he died. I would never say something like that."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =May 3, 2001 
  | url =http://www.freemumia.com/beverlydeclaration.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>}}

For a similar period, William Cook also did not [[testimony|testify]] or make any statement whatsoever about events other than his utterance at the crimescene:{{cquote|I ain't got nothing to do with this.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Lopez
  | first =Steve
  | coauthors =
  | title =Wrong Guy, Good Cause
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =[[Time Magazine]]
  | date =July 23, 2000
  | url =http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,50613,00.html
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>}} On April 29, 2001, he belatedly authored a declaration to the effect that he would be willing to testify and that both he and his brother "had nothing do with shooting or killing the policeman".<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of William Cook
  | work =
  | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
  | date =April 29, 2001
  | url =http://www.freemumia.com/cookdeclaration.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

William Singletary has stated that he directly witnessed the entire incident and that he would be willing to testify that Abu-Jamal was not the gunman.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last ="Minister of Information JR"    
  | first =
  | coauthors =
  | title =William Singletary, eyewitness on the night Mumia was shot and framed - Part 2
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =San Francisco Bay View
  | date =June 19, 2007
  | url =http://www.sfbayview.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=229&Itemid=18 
  | accessdate =  }}
Interview with William Singletary published 19 June 2007</ref> Singletary's post-conviction review hearing testimony of August 11, 1995 described that police tore up two of his written statements and that he was prevailed upon to sign a different statement which they dictated.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Kissinger
  | first =C. Clark 
  | coauthors =
  | title =Analysis of the Pennsylvania Supreme Court Decision On Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =Revolutionary Worker #982
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Revolutionary Worker 
  | date =November 15, 1998
  | url =http://www.rwor.org/a/v20/980-89/982/court.htm  
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

[[Image:Singchair.jpg|thumb|right|A model of [[electric chair]]. [[Electrocution]] was employed as the means of judicial execution of [[death row]] prisoners in Pennsylvania from 1915 until November 29, 1990.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Historical information on the death penalty and executions in Pennsylvania 
  | work =
  | publisher =Pennsylvania Department of Corrections
  | date = 
  | url =http://www.cor.state.pa.us/deathpenalty/site/default.asp?portalNav=|
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>]] Court [[Shorthand|stenographer]] Terri Maurer-Carter stated in an affidavit of August 2001 that in the presence of herself and two others the presiding Judge had exclaimed:
{{cquote|"Yeah, and I'm going to help them [[electric chair|fry]] the [[nigger]]."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Statement of Terri Maurer-Carter
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =August 21, 2001 
  | url =http://www.labournet.net/mumia/0109/terrimc.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>}}regarding Abu-Jamal's case shortly before the start of the trial.<br />

On April 24, 2003, Kenneth Pate, the step-brother of Priscilla Durham, swore a declaration incorporating the following relevant content:<blockquote>"I read a newspaper article about the Mumia Abu-Jamal case. It said Priscilla Durham had testified at Abu-Jamal's trial that when she was working as a security guard at the hospital she heard Abu-Jamal say that he had killed the police officer. When I read this I realized it was a different story from what she had told me.” .. [when I asked her] .. "Did you hear him say that?”" [she] answered, "All I heard him say was: 'Get off me, get off me, they're trying to kill me'."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of Kenneth Pate
  | work =
  | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
  | date =April 18, 2003
  | url =http://www.mumia.de/doc/aktuell/20030510mde00en.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref></blockquote> 
Pate reported that the conversation occurred "sometime around the end of 1983 or the beginning of 1984", while he was in the same [[prison]] as Abu-Jamal. His affidavit was released during another period in which both he and Abu-Jamal were housed in the same prison - a time postdating the death of Ms Durham.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of Kenneth Pate
  | work =
  | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
  | date =April 18, 2003
  | url =http://www.mumia.de/doc/aktuell/20030510mde00en.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> Pate's affidavit has been tendered as evidence by Abu-Jamal’s lawyers to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
