=== Physical evidence === 
A .38 [[caliber]] [[handgun]] he had purchased to defend himself as a cab driver in 1979 was found at the scene next to him, containing 5 spent [[shell casings]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Developments in the Mumia Abu-Jamal case
  | work =
  | publisher =CNN.com/Law Center 
  | date =
  | url =http://archives.cnn.com/2001/LAW/12/18/chronology.abu.jamal 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia Reconsidered
  | work =
  | publisher =DC Indymedia 
  | date =November 6, 1998
  | url =http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/110698/index.php 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> [[Coroner]] Dr. Paul Hoyer, who [[autopsy|autopsied]] Daniel Faulkner, recorded in his examining report that he extracted a [[.44 Magnum|.44 caliber]] [[bullet]] noting  "shot w/ 44 cal". He later testified to the effect that his description of it had been a "rough guess" based on his own observations, that he was not a [[firearms]] expert and that he had not received any training in [[External ballistics|weapons ballistics]].<ref>Trial transcript for June 25, 1982.</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =Kissinger
  | first =C. Clark 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Building a Railroad: The Suppression, Manipulation and Fabrication of Evidence 
  | work =Revolutionary Worker #1044
  | publisher =Revolutionary Worker 
  | date =February 27, 2000
  | url =http://www.rwor.org/a/v21/1040-049/1044/habeas4.htm 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> 

Tests performed with the available physical evidence verify that Daniel Faulkner was killed by a .38 caliber bullet. The extracted slugs identified as [[Federal Cartridge|Federal brand]] [[.38 Special]] [[+P]] bullets with hollow bases. It may be noted that the hollow base in a +P bullet is distinguishable from Federal [[ammunition]] otherwise used at that time.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =.38 Special LSWCHP +P: Still a Top Load? 
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.hipowersandhandguns.com/38%20Special%20158gr%20LSWCHP.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> The type, brand, and caliber of the extracted bullets all match those of the shell casings obtained from Abu-Jamal's [[Charter Arms]] [[revolver]] which was retrieved at the scene. That manufacturer is known for [[rifling]] the barrels of their revolvers with eight lands and grooves. Anthony L. Paul, Supervisor of the Firearms Identification Unit, could name two other manufacturers "right off the bat" who produce weapons with eight lands and grooves with a right-hand direction of twist.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Testimony of Anthony L. Paul, Supervisor Firearms Identification Unit, Philadelphia Police Department. 1982 trial transcripts at p.168 for June 23, 1982.
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>  

Experts testified that the bullet taken from Abu-Jamal had been fired from Daniel Faulkner's service weapon. George Fassnacht, a ballistics expert proferred by the defense, did not dispute any of the prosecution's findings.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =MUMIA ABU-JAMAL, Petitioner, v. MARTIN HORN, Commissioner, Pennsylvania Department of Corrections, ET AL., Respondents. Memorandum and Order
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.paed.uscourts.gov/documents/opinions/01D0951P.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> 

[[Amnesty International]] has made reference to the physical evidence to the extent of expressing their view that there was: <blockquote>".. a lack of adequate [[Ballistic fingerprinting|ballistic tests]] to determine whether [Abu-Jamal's] gun had recently been fired. It was not determined, for instance, whether there was [[gunshot residue|residue]] on his hands from firing a [[gun]]."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =USA: Mumia Abu-Jamal -- Amnesty International calls for retrial
  | work =
  | publisher =Amnesty International, USA
  | date =
  | url =http://web.amnesty.org/library/Index/engAMR510202000 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref></blockquote>

In a 1995 hearing, another defense ballistics expert testified that due to Abu-Jamal's struggle with the police during his arrest, such a test would have been difficult to accomplish and, due to the [[gunpowder]] residue possibly being shaken or rubbed off, would not have been scientifically reliable.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =COMMONWEALTH VS. MUMIA ABU-JAMAL aka WESLEY COOK - Post Conviction Review Act hearing transcripts of February 8, 1995
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/pcra/95-08-02.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> 

The jury delivered a guilty [[verdict]] after five hours of [[deliberation]]s.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (see p.2)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> In the sentencing phase of the trial Abu-Jamal read from a prepared statement without being sworn or examined by the attorney for either party, and he declined to call any mitigating witnesses.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =December 2001 
  | url =http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> In his statement to the jury he criticised his attorney as a "legal trained lawyer" who was imposed on him against his will who "knew he was inadequate to the task and chose to follow the directions of this black-robed conspirator, [Judge] Albert Sabo, even if it meant ignoring my directions." He claimed that all his rights had been "deceitfully stolen" from him by the Judge, particularly focusing on the denial of his request to receive defence assistance from John Africa and his being prevented from proceding pro se. He quoted remarks of John Africa and declared himself "innocent of these charges".<ref>{{cite court
  |litigants=Commonwealth vs. Mumia Abu-Jamal aka Wesley Cook
  |vol=
  |reporter=
  |opinion=
  |pinpoint=pp.10-16 of transcript
  |court=Court of Common Please, Philadelphia Criminal Trial Division
  |date=July 3, 1982
  |url= }}</ref>

== Death sentence and reactions ==
[[Image:Free Mumia.jpg|thumb|200px|right|"Free Mumia" parking garage stencil with "Cop killer" [[graffito]].]][[Image:040705 009 bristol maj m32.jpg|thumb|An anarchist mural in inner-city [[Bristol]], [[England]]]]Abu-Jamal was subsequently [[death sentence|sentenced to death]] by the [[unanimous]] [[decision]] of his jury<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (see p.3)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }} </ref> on July 3, 1982.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =December 2001 
  | url =http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> The date of the sentence is recorded as May 25, 1983.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Persons sentenced to execution in Pennsylvania as of August 1, 2007
  | work =
  | publisher =Pennsylvania Department of Corrections
  | date =
  | url =http://www.cor.state.pa.us/portal/lib/portal/Execution_List.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =August 31, 2007}}</ref> Judicial execution in Pennsylvania is by means of [[lethal injection]] and would occur at the [[State Correctional Institution - Rockview]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Information re death penalty and executions in Pennsylvania
  | work =
  | publisher =Pennsylvania Department of Corrections 
  | date =
  | url =http://www.cor.state.pa.us/deathpenalty/site/default.asp 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> 

The Philadelphia Office of the [[District Attorney]], Daniel Faulkner's family, the [[Fraternal Order of Police]], and numerous other law-enforcement-related organizations have expressed approval of the conviction and [[sentence (law)|sentence]] - being of a view that Abu-Jamal murdered Daniel Faulkner while the latter was making a lawful arrest in the line of police duty, and that Abu-Jamal had received a [[fair trial]]. Maureen Faulkner, the wife of the deceased, has been a notably vehement advocate for the cause of upholding the verdict and original sentence.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Cavanaugh
  | first =Andrea
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =  | title =Slain cop's widow wages long campaign to see justice done
  | work =
  | publisher =[[MSNBC]] from Ventura County Star
  | date =December 9, 2001
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/newsarticles/others/slaincopswidow/slaincopswidow.html  
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

District Attorney [[Lynne Abraham]], who at times has supervised aspects of the Abu-Jamal case, is on record stating that the matter of the death of Daniel Faulkner was the "most open-and-shut murder case" she'd ever tried,<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Gibson
  | first =Dave 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =25 Years Later...Still No Justice for Officer Daniel Faulkner 
  | work =
  | publisher =The American Daily
  | date =January 13, 2007 
  | url =http://www.americandaily.com/article/17215
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> and that Abu-Jamal: <blockquote>"Never produced his own brother, who was present at the time of the murder, (yet) he has offered up various individuals who would claim that one trial witness or another must have [[lie]]d; or that some other individual has only recently been discovered who has special knowledge about the murder; or that someone has fallen out of the skies, who is supposedly willing to confess to the murder of Officer Faulkner."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Saunders
  | first =Debra J.
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia finds safety in numbers 
  | work =
  | publisher =Jewish World Review
  | date =December 21, 2001 
  | url =http://www.jewishworldreview.com/1201/saunders122101.asp 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref></blockquote>

== Appeals and legal developments ==
{{main|Mumia Abu-Jamal legal proceedings}}
=== 1989 - 2000 State appeals ===
Direct appeal of his conviction was considered and denied by the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania]] on March 6, 1989,<ref>{{cite court
  |litigants=Pennsylvania v. Abu-Jamal
  |vol=555
  |reporter=A.2d 
  |opinion=846
  |pinpoint=
  |court=
  |date=1989
  |url= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (see p.3)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> subsequently denying rehearing.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =December 2001
  | url =http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> On October 1, 1990, the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] denied his appeal for [[certiorari|writ of certiorari]],<ref>{{cite court
  |litigants=Abu-Jamal v. Pennsylvania
  |vol=498
  |reporter=U.S.
  |opinion=881 
  |pinpoint=
  |court=
  |date=1990
  |url= }}</ref> and his [[petition]] for rehearing twice up to June 10,1991.<ref>{{cite court
  |litigants=Abu-Jamal v. Pennsylvania
  |vol=501
  |reporter=U.S.
  |opinion=1214
  |pinpoint=
  |court=
  |date=1991
  |url= }}</ref><ref>http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf December 2001 US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn detailing the history, progression, and outcomes of all prior post-conviction appeals</ref> 

[[Image:Tom Ridge.jpg|thumb|100px|left|Tom Ridge]]On June 1, 1995 his [[execution warrant|death warrant]] was signed by Pennsylvania Governor [[Tom Ridge]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (see p.3)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> Its execution was suspended while Abu-Jamal pursued post-conviction review,<ref>ibid. p.4</ref> the outcome of which was a unanimous decision by six judges of the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania]] on October 31, 1998 that all issues raised by him were without merit.<ref>ibid. p.5</ref> On October 13, 1999, Governor Ridge signed a second death warrant.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =December 2001 
  | url =http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

=== 2001 Federal ruling directing resentencing ===
[[William H. Yohn, Jr.|Judge William H. Yohn Jr.]] of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania]] [[Void (law)|voided]] the sentence of death on December 18, 2001, citing "irregularities" in the original process of sentencing.<ref>December 2001 US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn</ref> 
Particularly,<blockquote>"When the jury instructions and verdict sheet employed in Jamal’s case are considered, it becomes apparent that there is a reasonable likelihood that the jury has applied the . . . instruction [and form] in a way that prevents the consideration of [[constitutionalism|constitutionally relevant]] evidence, regarding the existence of any named [[mitigation|mitigating]] circumstances."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =From the December 2001 US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn in MUMIA ABU-JAMAL v. MARTIN HORN (Commissioner, Pennsylvania Department of Corrections), ET AL.
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref></blockquote> He ordered the State of Pennsylvania to commence sentencing proceedings anew within 180 days<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =
  | first =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Abu-Jamal's death sentence overturned
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =BBC News
  | date =December 18, 2001
  | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/1718274.stm 
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> and ruled that it was [[unconstitutional]] to require that a jury's finding of the existence of circumstances mitigating against determining a sentence of death be restricted to unanimous findings with respect to pre-defined, discrete and exclusive categories of factors.<ref>See p.70 of the July 2006 appeal brief for Mumia Abu-Jamal before the US Court of Appeal citing the ruling of Judge Yohn in the US District Court, the [[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], and the [[United States Supreme Court]] [[precedent]] of ''Mills v Maryland'', 486 U.S. 367 (1988)</ref> Eliot Grossman and Marlene Kamish, attorneys for Abu-Jamal, criticised the ruling on the grounds that it denied the possibility of a [[trial de novo]] at which they could lead evidence to establish their case that their client had been the subject of a [[frameup]].<ref>{{cite press release
  | title =Mumia still waiting for due process
  | publisher =International Concerned Family 
and Friends of Mumia Abu Jamal - Betsey Piette
  | date =March 6, 2003
  | url =http://www.mumia2000.org/alerts/legalupdate3-03.html
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> Both [[Party (law)|parties]] appealed.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Muhammad
  | first =Jerry 
  | coauthors =
  | title =From France to Philadelphia: An evening of solidarity with Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =FinalCall.com News
  | date =July 17, 2006
  | url =http://www.finalcall.com/artman/publish/article_2775.shtml
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Lindorff
  | first =Dave 
  | coauthors =
  | title =Reversal of Fortune? Mumia’s death sentence is overturned, for now
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =inthesetimes.com
  | date =December 22, 2001
  | url =http://www.inthesetimes.com/issue/26/04/news3.shtml 
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

=== 2005 Federal higher appeal ===
[[Image:Gov Ed Rendell.jpg|thumb|100px|right|Ed Rendell]]
On December 6, 2005, the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]] admitted four issues for appeal of the ruling of the United States District Court:<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Lindorff 
  | first =Dave 
  | coauthors =
  | title =A victory for Mumia
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Salon.com
  | date =December 8, 2005
  | url =http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2005/12/08/mumia/index.html 
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Bennett 
  | first =Hans 
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia's Oral Arguments set for May 17
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Pittsburgh Independent Media Center
  | date =April 4, 2007
  | url =http://pittsburgh.indymedia.org/news/2007/04/27101.php 
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>
* in relation to sentencing, whether the jury verdict form had been flawed and the judge's instructions to the jury had been confusing 
* in relation to conviction and sentencing, whether racial bias in [[jury selection]] existed to an extent tending to produce an inherently biased and unprofessional jury and therefore an unfair trial (the ''[[Batson v. Kentucky|Batson]]'' claim)  
* in relation to conviction, whether the prosecutor improperly attempted to reduce jurors' sense of responsibility by telling them that a guilty verdict would be subsequently [[vetting|vetted]] and subject to appeal
* in relation to post-conviction review hearings in 1995-6, whether the presiding Judge - who had also presided at the trial - demonstrated unacceptable bias in his conduct.

[[Image:Freygang - Mumia Abu-Jamal 03.jpg|thumb|180px|right|May 12, 2007, concert performance as part of a ''Free Mumia'' demonstration in [[Germany]]]]
On March 17, 2006, the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania filed its appeal seeking to reinstate the sentence of death. [[Pennsylvania Governor]] [[Ed Rendell]] has pledged to sign a third execution warrant should the appeal be upheld in that regard.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Muhammad
  | first =Jerry 
  | coauthors =
  | title =From France to Philadelphia: An evening of solidarity with Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =FinalCall.com News
  | date =July 17, 2006
  | url =http://www.finalcall.com/artman/publish/article_2775.shtml
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Lindorff
  | first =Dave 
  | coauthors =
  | title =Reversal of Fortune?
Mumia’s death sentence is overturned, for now
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =inthesetimes.com
  | date =December 22, 2001
  | url =http://www.inthesetimes.com/issue/26/04/news3.shtml 
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> On [[October 23]], [[2006]], Abu-Jamal's [[counsel]] filed their reply [[Brief (law)|brief]]. They asked the Third Circuit Court to reverse the prior ruling on the basis that it would be the "only [[Judicial remedy|remedy]] .. available to correct .. injustice and excessive [[bias]] that .. denied [him] a fair trial".<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =October 2006 reply brief to the US Court of Appeal on behalf of Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | publisher =Prisonradio.org
  | date =
  | url =http://www.prisonradio.org/documents/pdf/2006OC~5.PDF
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

The Third Circuit Court heard [[oral argument]]s in the appeals on May 17, 2007, at the United States Courthouse in Philadelphia.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Partisan Defense Committee Says: For Class-Struggle Defense to Free Mumia Now!
  | work =
  | publisher =Partisan Defense Committee
  | date =May 19, 2007
  | url =http://www.partisandefense.org/pubs/press/2007-05-19.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>
The appeal panel consisted of Chief Judge [[Anthony Joseph Scirica]], Judge Thomas Ambro, and Judge Robert Cowen. Maureen Faulkner traveled from [[Southern California]] to be in attendance.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia Abu-Jamal's case before Federal court
  | work =
  | publisher =Philadelphia Inquirer
  | date =May 17, 2007
  | url =http://www.philly.com/philly/hp/news_update/20070517_Mumia_Abu-Jamals_case_before_federal_court.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> Abu-Jamal's attorneys sought to obtain a new trial, while the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania challenged Judge Yohn's ruling insofar as it had presumed to invalidate the outcome of the original sentencing procedure.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Appeals court won't step down from Abu-Jamal case
  | work =
  | publisher =Philadelphia Inquirer
  | date =April 21, 2007
  | url =http://www.philly.com/dailynews/national/20070421_Appeals_court_wont_step_down_from_Abu-Jamal_case.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

== Life as a prisoner ==
=== Disciplinary ===
On August 31, 1982 he was [[Segregation|segregated]] after a fight with [[prison officer|guards]] at [[Holmesburg#Prisons|Holmesburg Prison]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Everything2.com about Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | publisher =Everything2.com
  | date =
  | url =http://www.everything2.com/index.pl?node_id=150221 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

=== Activism, writings, educational pursuits ===
Since imprisonment, Abu-Jamal has continued his political activism, publishing ''Live from Death Row'', a book on life inside prisons, and other works during the more recent years of his incarceration (see [[Mumia Abu-Jamal#Sources|Sources]]). He has attained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Goddard College]] and a [[Master of Arts (postgraduate)|Master of Arts]] from [[California State University, Dominguez Hills]], both by [[distance education]] during the course of his imprisonment. The [http://newcollege.edu/law/index.cfm New College of California School of Law] has presented him with an honorary [[J.D.]] degree.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =New College of California School of Law - list of honorary degree recipients
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.newcollege.edu/law/honorary_degrees.cfm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

=== Claim of 1992 confession ===
In 1999, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' revealed that a volunteer named Phillip Bloch visited Abu-Jamal in prison in 1992 and asked him whether he regretted killing Faulkner, to which it was reported that he replied: {{cquote|"Yes."<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Bissinger
  | first =Buzz 
  | coauthors =
  | title =The Famous And The Dead
  | work =
  | pages =6
  | language =
  | publisher =Vanity Fair
  | date =August 1999
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/VanityFair.pdf 
  | accessdate =  }}
See p.6</ref>}}
Bloch, otherwise a supporter of Abu-Jamal's case, stated he came forward after he grew concerned about the [[Character assassination|vilification]] of Daniel Faulkner. In response, Abu-Jamal is reported to have said "A lie is a lie, whether made today or 10 years later", and thanked ''Vanity Fair'' "...not for their work but for stoking this controversy, because controversy leads to questioning, and one can only question this belated confession."<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Mackler
  | first =Jeff 
  | coauthors =
  | title =Vanity Fair and ABC-TV Stories of Mumia's 'Confession' Collapse
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Socialist Action
  | date =August 1999
  | url =http://www.socialistaction.org/news/199908/confession.html 
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

=== NPR contract ===
In May 1994 Abu-Jamal was commercially engaged by [[National Public Radio]]'s ''[[All Things Considered]]'' program to deliver a series of monthly 3-minute commentaries addressing issues of [[crime]] and [[punishment]].<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Carter
  | first =Kevin L
  | coauthors =
  | title =A voice of Death Row to be heard on NPR
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Philadelphia Inquirer
  | date =May 16, 1994
  | url =http://www.fortunecity.com/meltingpot/botswana/509/inqarticles/5-16-94.htm
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> The broadcast plans and commercial arrangement were cancelled following condemnatory public outcry in anticipation encouraged by the Fraternal Order of Police.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Carter
  | first =Kevin L
  | coauthors =
  | title =Inmate's broadcasts cancelled
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Philadelphia Inquirer
  | date =May 17, 1994
  | url =http://www.fortunecity.com/meltingpot/botswana/509/inqarticles/5-17-94.htm 
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> The commentaries appeared in print in May 1995.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =
  | first =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Inmate's commentaries, dropped by NPR, will appear in print
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Philadelphia Enquirer
  | date =March 6, 1995
  | url =http://www.fortunecity.com/meltingpot/botswana/509/inqarticles/3-6-95.htm 
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

=== "Public speaking" ===
In 1999, Abu-Jamal was invited to deliver the keynote address for the graduating class at [[The Evergreen State College]].<ref>{{cite press release
  | title =Mumia Abu-Jamal to Speak at College Graduation Ceremonies 
  | publisher =Peter Bohmer of Evergreen State College, [[Washington State]]
  | date =May 26, 1999
  | url =http://academic.evergreen.edu/b/bohmerp/znetmay99.htm
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> He accepted, and a recording of his speech was played at the commencement ceremony, being that he was not legally permitted to attend in person. The event was protested heavily by police officers from around the US. Among other schools whose graduates he has addressed are [[Antioch College]], [[UC Santa Cruz]], [[Kent State University]], [[Occidental College]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Reynolds 
  | first =Mark 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Whatever Happened to Mumia Abu-Jamal?
  | work =
  | publisher =Popmatters.com
  | date =June 2, 2004
  | url =http://www.popmatters.com/columns/reynolds/040602.shtml
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> His radio program airs regularly and may be listened to online at [[Prison Radio]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Abu-Jamal
  | first =Mumia 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia Abu-Jamal's Radio Broadcasts - essay transcripts and archived mp3 recordings
  | work =
  | publisher =PrisonRadio.org
